---
import PageShell from '../../../../components/PageShell.astro';
import CTABox from '../../../../components/CTABox.astro';
import ComparisonTable from '../../../../components/ComparisonTable.astro';

const tocItems = [
  { id: 'overview', text: 'Overview', level: 2 },
  { id: 'healthcare-system', text: 'Healthcare System', level: 2 },
  { id: 'visa-requirements', text: 'Visa Options', level: 2 },
  { id: 'insurance-requirements', text: 'Insurance Requirements', level: 2 },
  { id: 'recommended-providers', text: 'Recommended Providers', level: 2 },
  { id: 'costs', text: 'Expected Costs', level: 2 },
  { id: 'scenarios', text: 'Real-World Scenarios', level: 2 },
  { id: 'faqs', text: 'Common Questions', level: 2 },
];

const relatedLinks = [
  { title: 'Indonesia Insurance Guide', href: '/countries/indonesia/insurance' },
  { title: 'Insurance for Seniors', href: '/insurance-for/seniors' },
  { title: 'Indonesia Second Home Visa', href: '/visas/retirement-visa/in/indonesia' },
  { title: 'Thailand for Seniors', href: '/insurance-for/seniors/in/thailand' },
  { title: 'Malaysia for Seniors', href: '/insurance-for/seniors/in/malaysia' },
];

const providerColumns = [
  { key: 'provider', header: 'Provider' },
  { key: 'entryAge', header: 'Max Entry Age' },
  { key: 'renewal', header: 'Renewal' },
  { key: 'monthlyFrom', header: 'From (65-69)' },
  { key: 'indonesiaFit', header: 'Indonesia Fit' },
];

const providerRows = [
  { provider: 'Cigna Global', entryAge: '74', renewal: 'Lifetime', monthlyFrom: '$340-470/mo', indonesiaFit: 'Excellent' },
  { provider: 'BUPA Global', entryAge: '79', renewal: 'Lifetime', monthlyFrom: '$420-600/mo', indonesiaFit: 'Excellent' },
  { provider: 'Allianz Care', entryAge: '74', renewal: 'Lifetime', monthlyFrom: '$310-440/mo', indonesiaFit: 'Very Good' },
  { provider: 'Pacific Cross Indonesia', entryAge: '65', renewal: '75', monthlyFrom: '$150-280/mo', indonesiaFit: 'Excellent (Local)' },
  { provider: 'Allianz Indonesia', entryAge: '65', renewal: '70', monthlyFrom: '$120-250/mo', indonesiaFit: 'Good (Local)' },
];

const costColumns = [
  { key: 'category', header: 'Expense' },
  { key: 'monthly', header: 'Monthly' },
  { key: 'annual', header: 'Annual' },
];

const costRows = [
  { category: 'International Insurance (65-69)', monthly: '$320-470', annual: '$3,840-5,640' },
  { category: 'International Insurance (70-74)', monthly: '$450-650', annual: '$5,400-7,800' },
  { category: 'International Insurance (75-79)', monthly: '$600-880', annual: '$7,200-10,560' },
  { category: 'Indonesian Local Insurance', monthly: '$120-300', annual: '$1,440-3,600' },
  { category: 'Second Home Visa Insurance', monthly: 'Required', annual: 'Varies by provider' },
];
---

<PageShell
  title="Health Insurance for Seniors in Indonesia & Bali | Retirement Guide"
  description="Guide to health insurance for seniors retiring in Indonesia and Bali. Second Home visa, BIMC Hospital, evacuation coverage, and options for expats 70+."
  headline="Health Insurance for Seniors in Indonesia"
  subheadline="Bali offers paradise living at affordable prices—but healthcare limitations mean international insurance with evacuation coverage is essential."
  heroImage="/images/countries/indonesia-hero-bg.png"
  tocItems={tocItems}
  relatedLinks={relatedLinks}
  ctaButtonText="Compare Senior Plans →"
  ctaButtonHref="/go/cigna-global"
>
  <h2 id="overview">Why Seniors Choose Indonesia</h2>
  <p>
    Indonesia, particularly Bali, has become increasingly popular with retirees seeking tropical paradise at affordable prices. The island's spiritual atmosphere, welcoming culture, beautiful landscapes, and established expat communities create an appealing retirement environment.
  </p>

  <p>
    Bali attracts most retirees, with areas like Ubud (cultural heart), Sanur (quiet beach town popular with older expats), Seminyak (more developed), and Canggu (surfer vibe) offering different lifestyles. Jakarta provides urban amenities and the best healthcare, while Lombok offers a quieter alternative to Bali.
  </p>

  <div class="bg-primary-50 border border-primary-200 rounded-lg p-6 my-6">
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-primary-900 mb-3">Key Facts for Seniors</h3>
    <ul class="text-primary-800 space-y-2">
      <li><strong>Healthcare:</strong> Limited in Bali; excellent in Jakarta/Singapore</li>
      <li><strong>Language:</strong> English common in tourist areas; Indonesian elsewhere</li>
      <li><strong>Cost of living:</strong> $1,500-2,500/month comfortable in Bali</li>
      <li><strong>Climate:</strong> Tropical; dry season April-October</li>
      <li><strong>Visa:</strong> New Second Home Visa makes long-term stay easier</li>
    </ul>
  </div>

  <h2 id="healthcare-system">Indonesia's Healthcare System</h2>
  <p>
    Healthcare quality in Indonesia varies dramatically by location. Understanding this is crucial for retirement planning, especially for seniors who may need medical care.
  </p>

  <h3>Healthcare in Bali</h3>
  <p>
    Bali has several international clinics and hospitals, but facilities are limited compared to Bangkok or Singapore. Major options include:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>BIMC Hospital (Kuta, Nusa Dua):</strong> International standard; expat-focused; 24/7 emergency</li>
    <li><strong>Siloam Hospital (Denpasar):</strong> Part of large Indonesian chain; good facilities</li>
    <li><strong>Kasih Ibu Hospital:</strong> Local private hospital; adequate for basic needs</li>
    <li><strong>International SOS (Bali):</strong> Evacuation and emergency coordination</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    For serious conditions, many expats fly to:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Singapore:</strong> 2.5 hours; world-class hospitals</li>
    <li><strong>Jakarta:</strong> 1.5 hours; excellent private hospitals</li>
    <li><strong>Bangkok:</strong> 4 hours; medical tourism hub</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Healthcare Costs in Bali</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>GP at international clinic:</strong> $50-100</li>
    <li><strong>Specialist at BIMC:</strong> $80-150</li>
    <li><strong>Hospital day (private room):</strong> $200-500</li>
    <li><strong>MRI:</strong> $300-600</li>
    <li><strong>Complex surgery:</strong> Often requires evacuation</li>
  </ul>

  <div class="bg-amber-50 border border-amber-200 rounded-lg p-6 my-6">
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-amber-900 mb-3">Evacuation is Essential</h3>
    <p class="text-amber-800">
      Unlike Thailand or Malaysia, Bali has significant healthcare limitations for serious conditions. Complex cardiac surgery, major cancer treatment, and advanced neurology often require evacuation to Singapore or Jakarta. Any insurance for Bali must include robust evacuation coverage—this is non-negotiable for seniors.
    </p>
  </div>

  <h2 id="visa-requirements">Visa Options for Senior Retirees</h2>
  <p>
    Indonesia has historically been challenging for long-term retirement, but new visa options have improved the situation.
  </p>

  <h3>Second Home Visa (2022+)</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Financial requirement:</strong> $130,000 in Indonesian bank OR $2 billion IDR (~$130,000) property</li>
    <li><strong>Duration:</strong> 5-10 years</li>
    <li><strong>Health insurance:</strong> Required</li>
    <li><strong>Age:</strong> No minimum</li>
    <li><strong>Work:</strong> Cannot work for Indonesian employer</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Retirement KITAS (Previous Option)</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Age:</strong> 55+ years old</li>
    <li><strong>Financial:</strong> $1,500/month pension or proof of funds</li>
    <li><strong>Insurance:</strong> Required from Indonesian company</li>
    <li><strong>Duration:</strong> 1 year, renewable up to 5 years</li>
    <li><strong>Status:</strong> Being replaced by Second Home Visa</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Social/Cultural Visa + Extensions</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Duration:</strong> 60 days, extendable to 180 days</li>
    <li><strong>Approach:</strong> Multiple entries with visa runs</li>
    <li><strong>Notes:</strong> Less stable; requires periodic travel</li>
  </ul>

  <CTABox
    title="Planning Your Bali Retirement?"
    description="Get coverage with evacuation to Singapore or Jakarta."
    buttonText="Compare Plans →"
    buttonHref="/go/cigna-global"
    variant="highlight"
  />

  <h2 id="insurance-requirements">Insurance Requirements for Seniors</h2>
  <p>
    Indonesia's visa options increasingly require health insurance. More importantly, insurance is practically essential given Bali's healthcare limitations.
  </p>

  <h3>Second Home Visa Requirements</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>Health insurance covering Indonesia required</li>
    <li>Indonesian or international insurance accepted</li>
    <li>Must be valid for visa duration</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Why International Insurance is Critical</h3>
  <p>
    For seniors in Bali, international insurance with evacuation is essential:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Evacuation coverage:</strong> Singapore/Jakarta evacuation costs $20,000-50,000+</li>
    <li><strong>Treatment abroad:</strong> Complex procedures not available in Bali</li>
    <li><strong>Direct billing:</strong> Major insurers bill directly at BIMC</li>
    <li><strong>Regional network:</strong> Access to Singapore, Bangkok, Jakarta hospitals</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Minimum Recommended Coverage</h3>
  <p>
    For Bali retirement, ensure your policy includes:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>Medical evacuation with no sub-limits</li>
    <li>Coverage in Singapore (evacuation destination)</li>
    <li>Direct billing at BIMC and international hospitals</li>
    <li>Repatriation coverage</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 id="recommended-providers">Recommended Providers for Indonesia</h2>
  <p>
    These insurers work well for seniors in Indonesia:
  </p>

  <div class="my-8 border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg overflow-hidden">
    <ComparisonTable columns={providerColumns} rows={providerRows} />
  </div>

  <h3>Cigna Global</h3>
  <p>
    Excellent choice for Bali. Direct billing at BIMC. Strong evacuation coverage to Singapore. Entry up to 74 with lifetime renewal. Regional network includes Singapore, Bangkok, Jakarta hospitals.
  </p>

  <h3>BUPA Global</h3>
  <p>
    Accepts applicants up to 79—essential for seniors 75+. Comprehensive worldwide coverage with excellent evacuation benefits. Premium pricing but reliable for those needing coverage above 74.
  </p>

  <h3>Pacific Cross Indonesia</h3>
  <p>
    Local specialist in expatriate coverage. Good understanding of Indonesian healthcare system. Entry up to 65 with renewal to 75. Direct billing at major hospitals. More affordable than international plans.
  </p>

  <h3>International SOS</h3>
  <p>
    Not traditional insurance but provides evacuation membership (~$500-1,000/year). Can supplement local insurance. 24/7 coordination for medical emergencies. Consider if primary insurance has evacuation limits.
  </p>

  <CTABox
    title="Compare Plans with Evacuation"
    description="Essential coverage for Bali's healthcare limitations."
    buttonText="See Options →"
    buttonHref="/go/cigna-global"
  />

  <h2 id="costs">Expected Insurance Costs</h2>
  <p>
    Insurance costs for Indonesia are moderate, but comprehensive evacuation coverage is worth the investment:
  </p>

  <div class="my-8 border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg overflow-hidden">
    <ComparisonTable columns={costColumns} rows={costRows} />
  </div>

  <h3>The Evacuation Factor</h3>
  <p>
    Without evacuation coverage, a medical emergency could cost:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Air ambulance to Singapore:</strong> $25,000-50,000</li>
    <li><strong>Commercial flight evacuation:</strong> $5,000-15,000</li>
    <li><strong>Singapore hospital treatment:</strong> $50,000-200,000+ for major procedures</li>
    <li><strong>Total potential exposure:</strong> $100,000-300,000+</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Cost-Saving Strategies</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Never skip evacuation:</strong> This is the one thing you can't self-insure in Bali</li>
    <li><strong>High deductible:</strong> Routine Bali care is affordable; insure the big stuff</li>
    <li><strong>Use local clinics:</strong> Not everything requires BIMC pricing</li>
    <li><strong>Regional coverage:</strong> Asia-only plan costs less than worldwide</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 id="scenarios">Real-World Scenarios</h2>

  <div class="grid gap-6 my-8">
    <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Scenario 1: Routine Care in Ubud</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-3">Linda, 71, needs checkup and blood pressure medication.</p>
      <p class="text-green-700"><strong>Outcome:</strong> Visits local clinic in Ubud. Consultation $25, bloodwork $40, 3-month medication $30. Total: $95. Below deductible—pays out-of-pocket. Good quality for routine care.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Scenario 2: Emergency at BIMC</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-3">Robert, 69, has severe abdominal pain in Sanur.</p>
      <p class="text-green-700"><strong>Outcome:</strong> Rushed to BIMC Nusa Dua. CT scan, diagnosis of appendicitis, surgery same day. Total bill: $8,500. Cigna Global covers after $2,500 deductible. Direct billing—smooth process.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Scenario 3: Cardiac Event Requiring Evacuation</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-3">James, 74, has heart attack in Canggu.</p>
      <p class="text-amber-700"><strong>Outcome:</strong> BIMC stabilizes. Needs cardiac surgery not available in Bali. Air ambulance to Mount Elizabeth Singapore—$42,000. Surgery and 10-day recovery—$85,000. Total: $127,000. BUPA Global covers fully. This is why evacuation coverage matters.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Scenario 4: Without Evacuation Coverage</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-3">Tom, 72, has only local insurance without evacuation.</p>
      <p class="text-red-700"><strong>Outcome:</strong> When he needs specialized surgery, must arrange and pay for own evacuation to Singapore. Air ambulance: $35,000 out-of-pocket. Surgery covered by separate Singapore policy he purchased, but evacuation bankrupting. Never skip evacuation coverage in Bali.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Scenario 5: Routine Specialist in Jakarta</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-3">Carol, 70, needs oncology follow-up (cancer survivor).</p>
      <p class="text-green-700"><strong>Outcome:</strong> Flies to Jakarta (1.5 hours, $100 flight). Sees specialist at Siloam Hospital. Consultation + scans: $400. Cigna Global covers. Quality equivalent to Singapore at lower cost.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Scenario 6: Senior Over 75 in Bali</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-3">Eleanor, 78, wants to retire in Sanur.</p>
      <p class="text-green-700"><strong>Outcome:</strong> Gets BUPA Global ($850/month)—one of few options at 78. Premium but includes evacuation. Lives in Sanur's established expat community. Uses BIMC for routine care, knows Singapore evacuation is covered for serious issues.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h2 id="faqs">Common Questions</h2>

  <div class="grid gap-6 my-8">
    <div class="bg-neutral-50 border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Is Bali healthcare really that limited?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-700">For routine care and many emergencies, Bali hospitals are adequate. BIMC handles appendectomies, fractures, and common conditions well. But for complex cardiac surgery, major cancer treatment, advanced neurology, or organ issues, evacuation to Singapore or Jakarta is standard practice. This is the reality of island healthcare.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-neutral-50 border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Can I get Indonesian local insurance?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-700">Yes, companies like Pacific Cross Indonesia, Allianz Indonesia, and AXA Mandiri offer local plans. Age limits typically 60-65 for new policies. They're more affordable but may have limited evacuation coverage. For seniors, international insurance with evacuation is safer.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-neutral-50 border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">I'm 77—what are my options?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-700">BUPA Global accepts up to 79. This is your main option for comprehensive coverage. Local Indonesian insurers typically stop at 65-70. At 77, BUPA Global for primary coverage, or self-insure routine care with standalone evacuation membership (International SOS).</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-neutral-50 border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">What's the Second Home Visa deposit?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-700">Approximately $130,000 in Indonesian bank account OR ownership of property worth ~$130,000 (2 billion IDR). This is higher than many retirement visas but provides 5-10 year stability. The deposit earns interest and can be withdrawn when you leave.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-neutral-50 border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">How do I arrange evacuation if needed?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-700">Good international insurers have 24/7 assistance lines. Call them, and they coordinate everything: air ambulance, receiving hospital in Singapore, medical escort. BIMC also has relationships with evacuation services. This is why direct billing and international network matter.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-neutral-50 border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Is Sanur really the best area for seniors?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-700">Sanur is known as "Snore" for its quieter pace—many see this as ideal for retirement. Established expat community, flat terrain (good for mobility), close to BIMC Nusa Dua, traditional feel. Ubud offers culture but hillier terrain. Seminyak/Canggu are younger and louder.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <CTABox
    title="Ready for Bali?"
    description="Find coverage with the evacuation protection Bali requires."
    buttonText="Compare Plans →"
    buttonHref="/go/cigna-global"
    variant="highlight"
  />

  <div class="bg-neutral-50 border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6 mt-8">
    <p class="text-sm text-neutral-600">
      <strong>Disclaimer:</strong> This guide is for informational purposes. Indonesian visa requirements, healthcare capabilities, and insurance options change. Verify current requirements with Indonesian immigration. Consider consulting a visa agent and insurance broker specializing in Indonesia. Always prioritize evacuation coverage for Bali retirement.
    </p>
  </div>
</PageShell>
